I wants to create excel and download it for huge data that can't be done by saving whole data in a buffer and then write into the xlsx file(Memory issue) so I tried using streams so that I can generate and download file on the fly without using much memory.

Here is my code : 
```javascript
const Excel = require("exceljs");

const createExcel = async resp => {
  //Setting up boilerplate for xlsx
  const workbook = new Excel.stream.xlsx.WorkbookWriter({ stream: resp });
  const worksheet = workbook.addWorksheet("Test");
  worksheet.state = "visible";
  worksheet.columns = [
    {
      header: "Name",
      key: "name",
      width: 20
    },
    {
      header: "Age",
      key: "age",
      width: 20
    },
    {
      header: "City",
      key: "city",
      width: 20
    }
  ];
  const limit = 20;
  let skip;
  //fetching huge data and adding it in xlsx using pagination
  while (true) {
    const { result } = await fetch(); //restAPI which returns array of json
    for (const element of result) {
      const { name, age, city } = element;
      worksheet
        .addRow({
          name,
          age,
          city
        })
        .commit();
    }
    if (result.length < limit) {
      await workbook.commit();
      return;
    }
    skip = { id: result[result.length - 1].id };
    console.log("Skip : ", skip);
  }
};

//Rest API to download xlsx
app.get("/download", (req, resp) => {
  resp.writeHead(200, {
    "Content-Type": "application/vnd.openxmlformats-officedocument.spreadsheetml.sheet",
    "Content-Disposition": `attachment; filename="${"outputFileName.xlsx"}"`,
    "Access-Control-Allow-Origin": "*",
    "Access-Control-Allow-Methods": "GET, POST, OPTIONS"
  });
  createExcel(resp);
});
```
I excpected that I would get chunks on browser/client side(from stream) whenever any row is committed but I am getting some 2800 KB data initially and rest data I am getting after committing workbook.

Am I doing something wrong here?
